# AckAgent PAM Service Configuration Example
#
# This file shows example PAM configurations for integrating
# the AckAgent PAM module with various services.

# =============================================================
# SSH Authentication
# =============================================================
# Add to /etc/pam.d/sshd before @include common-auth:
#
# # AckAgent push authentication (try first, fall back to password)
# auth    [success=done default=ignore]    pam_ackagent.so
#
# This configuration:
# - Attempts AckAgent push authentication first
# - If successful, skips remaining auth modules
# - If unsuccessful or timed out, continues to password auth
#
# For AckAgent-only authentication (no password fallback):
# auth    required    pam_ackagent.so

# =============================================================
# Sudo Authentication
# =============================================================
# Add to /etc/pam.d/sudo at the top:
#
# # AckAgent push authentication for sudo
# auth    sufficient    pam_ackagent.so
#
# This allows sudo with push approval, falling back to password.

# =============================================================
# System Login (TTY/Console)
# =============================================================
# Add to /etc/pam.d/login:
#
# # AckAgent push authentication
# auth    [success=done default=ignore]    pam_ackagent.so

# =============================================================
# Module Options
# =============================================================
# The PAM module accepts these optional arguments:
#
# config=/path/to/config.conf
#   - Use alternate configuration file
#   - Default: /etc/ackagent/pam.conf
#
# debug
#   - Enable debug logging to syslog
#
# timeout=N
#   - Override authentication timeout in seconds
#
# Example with options:
# auth sufficient pam_ackagent.so config=/etc/ackagent/custom.conf timeout=60 debug

# =============================================================
# Security Considerations
# =============================================================
# 1. Always test configuration changes with a backup session open
# 2. The "sufficient" control ensures fallback to password auth
# 3. Use "required" only if you're certain AckAgent is always available
# 4. Consider network outages - "sufficient" is safer than "required"
